            "description": "In the Arthur project, we develop a new method and handheld device for performing Sentinel Lymph Node mapping during surgery on breast cancer. Detecting these lymph nodes is usually performed by injection of a radioactive tracer, which is then followed with a gammaprobe. We aim to replace this method with a magnetic alternative, which uses superparamagnetic nanoparticles with a unique detection algorithm which negates the magnetic influence of the human body, which currently limits magnetic techniques for SLN mapping. Additional sensitivity is gained by combining our sensing technology with a miniature cryocooler from Kryoz, which decreases sensor noise due to added thermal stability and lower Johnson noise.\n\nIn this project, the University of Twente cooperates with two hospitals (MST Enschede and RUNMC Nijmegen) and three industry partners. \n\nMy responsibilities are to develop the sensing technology and hardware. In addition to this, I coordinate the work packages of the other partners and guarding the project's timeline and progress.",
